{
    "analysis": "You have already followed the prescribed workflow up through metric, trace, and log aggregate analysis. Key observations so far: (1) No non-zero error counts in logs or traces during the incident window — many error_rate/error_count series have global P95=0 and values=0, an artifact that should be ignored. (2) Metric anomalies (non-zero and actionable) were observed for a subset of allowed components: ts-route-service (socket spikes around 2024-01-24T22:56:00Z), ts-auth-service (cpu and diskio spikes around 22:51 and 23:01 UTC), and ts-travel-service (mem/socket/latency/workload spikes ~23:00–23:08 UTC). (3) log.row_count spikes occurred for ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, and ts-travel-service at various minutes within the window. Traces do not show non-zero error rates or clear latency escalations that would point to a specific downstream faulty service. The remaining step is fault identification: determine whether the metric anomalies for candidate components are isolated spikes or form consecutive faults, and the severity of those faults (how far beyond P95). This will enable root cause localization per the rules.",
