{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and anomaly detection across metrics, traces, and logs. Key findings so far: (1) Many error_count/error_rate series have global P95=0 and values=0 — these are artifacts and non-actionable. (2) Actionable metric anomalies (non-zero breaches) during the incident window were observed for a subset of allowed services: ts-route-service (socket, latency spikes ~22:56–23:03Z), ts-auth-service (cpu, diskio spikes ~22:51 & 23:01Z), ts-travel-service (mem/socket/workload/latency spikes ~23:00–23:08Z), and ts-order-service (diskio spike ~23:10Z). (3) Log row_count spikes occurred for several services at short durations; error logs returned no textual errors. To localize root cause we must determine which faulty service is the most downstream faulty service in the call chains and whether traces show latency/throughput anomalies aligned with metric faults. This requires focused trace inspection for traces involving the candidate services at the breach timestamps.",
